SIMPLE: inquisition
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inquisition
<hw>In`qui*si"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>inquisitio</ets> : cf. F. <ets>inquisition</ets>. See
<er>Inquire</er>, and cf. <er>Inquest</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
act of inquiring; inquiry; search; examination; inspection;
investigation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As I could learn through earnest <qex>inquisition</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let not search and <qex>inquisition</qex> quail⟦br⟧
To bring again these foolish runaways.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Judicial inquiry;
official examination; inquest.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The finding of a
jury, especially such a finding under a writ of inquiry.</def>
<rj><au>Bouvier.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The justices in eyre had it formerly in charge to make
<qex>inquisition</qex> concerning them by a jury of the county.</q>
<rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <def>A court or tribunal for the
examination and punishment of heretics, fully established by Pope
Gregory IX. in 1235. Its operations were chiefly confined to Spain,
Portugal, and their dependencies, and a part of Italy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inquisition</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Inquisition
<hw>In`qui*si"tion</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make inquisition
concerning; to inquire into.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inquisitional</ent>⟦br⟧
